%%TITLE
HPV status of oropharyngeal cancer by combination HPV DNA/p16 testing: biological relevance of discordant results.
%%ABSTRACT
Human papillomavirus (HPV) causes up to 70 % of oropharyngeal cancers (OSCC). HPV positive OSCC has a more favorable outcome, thus HPV status is being used to guide treatment and predict outcome. Combination HPV DNA/p16(ink4) (p16) testing is commonly used for HPV status, but there are no standardized methods, scoring or interpretative criteria. The significance of discordant (HPV DNA positive/p16 negative and HPV DNA negative/p16 positive) cancers is controversial. In this study, 647 OSCCs from 10 Australian centers were tested for HPV DNA/p16 expression. Our aims are to determine p16 distribution by HPV DNA status to inform decisions on p16 scoring and to assess clinical significance of discordant cancers.HPV DNA was identified using a multiplex tandem HPV E6 polymerase chain reaction (PCR) assay and p16 expression by semiquantitative immunohistochemistry.p16 distribution was essentially bimodal (42 % of cancers had â‰¥ 70 % positive staining, 52 % <5 % positive, 6 % between 5 and 70 %). Cancers with 5 to <50 % staining had similar characteristics to the p16 negative group, and cancers with 50 to <70 % staining were consistent with the â‰¥ 70 % group. Using a p16 cut-point of 50 %, there were 25 % HPV DNA positive/p16 negative cancers and 1 % HPV DNA negative/p16 positive cancers. HPV DNA positive/p16 negative cancers had outcomes similar to HPV DNA negative/p16 negative cancers.50 % is a reasonable cut-point for p16; HPV DNA positive/p16 negative OSCCs may be treated as HPV negative for clinical purposes; HPV DNA/p16 testing may add no prognostic information over p16 alone.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Study Population
Investigations were carried out on 647 patients treated with curative intent for primary OSCC at 10 Australian centers between 1979 and 2009. Demographic and clini- copathological data (Table ) were retrieved from institutional databases. The only selection criteria were availability of tumor and clinicopathological data. Patients were followed up for the occurrence of an event, defined as recurrence in any form or death from any cause, for a median of 34 (range 1–238) months after diagnosis. Patients who did not experience an event before the end of follow-up were known at that date to be alive and free of recurrence. The study was approved by the ethics com- mittees of all centers. The grade for cancers was reviewed by a pathologist (most by study pathologist C.S.L.) according to the World Health Organization (WHO) clas- sification of tumors.The majority of HPV positive cancers were poorly differentiated (Table ), in line with our previous report and published data.,,
Laboratory Studies
HPV DNA Testing The presence and type of HPV DNA were determined in one center by author G.H. on 4 9 5 lm formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded sections/cm2 of tissue using a multiplex tandem real-time PCR assay targeting
HPV E6 using modifications of the method of Stanley and Szewezuk.,This PCR assay simultaneously detects and identifies 21 HPV types (16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 39, 45, 51, 52, 56,
58, 59, 66, 68, 70, 73, 82, 53, 6, 11, and 26). Measured
amounts of equine herpesvirus were introduced in the extraction lysis buffer of each tissue section, and this was subsequently measured in a semiquantitative real-time assay to demonstrate that the extraction was efficient and also that PCR inhibitors had been removed. Positive clinical material (identity confirmed by DNA sequencing) for each HPV type was included in every test. The dose of these was calibrated to give a result just above the detection level. Negative controls were water blanks introduced between every fifth sample during the extraction process and which were assayed for HPV and equine herpesvirus together with samples, to control for laboratory contamination. Cycle threshold (Ct) values, which have an inverse relationship with virus copy number, were recorded.
Semiquantitative Immunohistochemistry In addition to p16, cancers were tested for cyclin D1 and epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) expression because of the inverse relationship between HPV and these proteins., Primary antibodies were p16 (clone JC2; Neomarkers, USA), cyclin D1 (clone SP4; Thermo Fisher Scientific, UK), and EGFR (clone 2-18C9; Dako, Australia). Procedures for determining expression including evaluation criteria were as described for p16, cyclin D1, and EGFR.,IHC was carried out and reviewed centrally (D.J., M.Z., C.S.L.). A section of cancer known to be positive for each antibody was included in every run. Substitution of primary and secondary antibodies with human serum provided negative controls. Since the MTM clone is now the most widely used p16 clone for HPV studies, 66 cancers were also tested with the MTM p16 antibody (1/200; MTM Laboratories, Germany) using the same detection procedures. The distribution, percentage, and intensity of staining in cancer and other cells were recorded. Immunostaining was evaluated centrally by three independent observers including the study pathologist (C.S.L.), all of whom were blinded to the clinical data. Positivity was defined as cytoplasmic and nuclear staining, except that two cancers with 50–70 % positive cells that had predominantly nuclear staining were also recorded as positive. Inconsistencies between observers were uncommon and were resolved over a double-headed microscope. Samples yielding discordant HPV DNA/p16 results were retested for both markers unless insufficient material was available.
Statistical Analyses
The Kaplan–Meier method was used to construct time- to-event curves. Univariate and multivariate time-to-event

Times to locoregional failure, death from tonsillar cancer, and death from any cause were cal- culated from date of diagnosis. Locoregional recurrence was defined as clinical, radiological or pathological evi- dence of recurrence at the primary site or in the regional nodal area. Patients who were not observed to experience a given event over the duration of the study were censored at the date of last follow-up, death from any cause (when estimating recurrence-free survival), or death from causes other than OSCC (when estimating disease-specific survival).
